            <p>
                However, there are also places where a subjunctive is used when no desire or condition is expressed. For
                example, it is often found when
                reporting something that was said, or following a verb of command. In many cases it is appropriate
                to translate these sentences with modal verbs such as 'should/would/could/might' in modern English, but
                sometimes the normal indicative
                form is fine. Examine the sentence below: '<em>Odda het ðæt he to him come</em>' which uses the singular
                subjunctive <em>come</em> with it's
                <strong>-e</strong> ending, and is perhaps best translated 'Odda ordered that he <em>should</em> come to
                him'.
            </p>
